### Notes

*   ^ It's worth a moment of your time to reflect that older operating systems, relics such as [DOS](/DOS) and the somewhat infamous [Windows&#160;3.1x](/Windows_3.1x) – systems that predated the widespread adoption of robust memory protection and virtual memory – fundamentally did not employ this sophisticated user space and kernel space architecture. In those simpler, more perilous times, applications often had direct, unfettered access to hardware and memory, leading to a rather fragile computing environment where a single errant program could bring down the entire system with alarming ease. It was, in essence, a digital free-for-all, a testament to how far we've come, despite our persistent flaws.

